------------------------------------------------------------------
THE CHALLENGE
------------------------------------------------------------------

We were given a file called image_94a0c5.png. The description
said to find a secret message left by the "sleeping capybara."
The image looked completely normal.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 1 -- LOAD INTO STEGSOLVE
------------------------------------------------------------------

When a PNG looks visually normal but hides data, bit-plane
analysis is the standard first move. StegSolve lets you isolate
individual color and bit planes of an image with arrow-key
navigation.

    java -jar StegSolve.jar

We opened image_94a0c5.png and cycled through all available
planes using the forward and backward arrows.

Remember: RGB images have three color channels (Red, Green,
Blue) and each channel has 8 bit planes (bit 0 through bit 7,
where bit 0 is the Least Significant Bit). StegSolve shows you
each plane as a black-and-white image. A plane with hidden data
will show structured patterns -- shapes, text, or QR codes --
that look completely different from the random noise you see in
a clean image's low bit planes.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 2 -- DISCOVER THE QR CODE
------------------------------------------------------------------

On the Blue 0 plane (the least significant bit of the blue
channel), a clear QR code appeared in the upper-right corner of
the image. It was completely invisible in the normal RGB view.

This is classic LSB steganography in a single color channel.
The QR code was embedded one bit at a time into the blue
channel's LSB across the pixels in that region. The visual
difference in blue intensity is too small for the human eye to
notice but StegSolve isolates it perfectly.

Remember: Blue 0 means the LSB (bit plane 0) of the Blue
channel. This is one of the most common hiding spots in PNG
steganography because the human eye is least sensitive to small
changes in blue compared to red and green. Always check all
three channel LSBs (Red 0, Green 0, Blue 0) when a PNG challenge
has no obvious clues.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 3 -- DECODE THE QR CODE
------------------------------------------------------------------

We saved the Blue 0 plane as an image from StegSolve using
File -> Save As, then scanned the QR code with any QR reader
(phone camera, or zxing online decoder).

The QR code decoded to a URL pointing to a pastebin page. The
pastebin contained the flag in plaintext.

Remember: when a QR code from StegSolve is hard to scan because
the image is small or blurry, save the plane image and upscale
it first using an image editor before scanning. Alternatively,
zxing.appspot.com accepts image uploads and is more tolerant of
low-resolution QR codes than phone cameras.

------------------------------------------------------------------
FULL COMMAND SEQUENCE
------------------------------------------------------------------

    java -jar StegSolve.jar
    -> Open image_94a0c5.png
    -> Cycle to Blue 0 plane
    -> QR code visible in upper-right corner
    -> File -> Save As -> blue0_plane.png
    Scan QR code -> URL -> pastebin -> flag

